@Spanner1969 thanks for the question. There are some alternate model choices which might close the gap between the model result and your measurements, but keep in mind, that irradiance models generally are 'average' models, over conditions and locations, and are not precise for any location or specific time. We default to the Ineichen clearsky model both for its simplicity and its performance relative to other simple models (see the Reno et al reference for the comparison).  Including altitude may help a bit, although the site you are modeling is already near sea level so this effect will be minor.

At some point in your modeling process you are transposing from horizontal to plane-of-array (probably with ` get_total_irradiance`) and that transposition defaults to the `isotropic` model, which is known to be biased towards low values.  You can select among other models for the transposition: I'd recommend `haydavies` for transposing modeled irradiance (and `perez` for transposing measurements).

Over a long period of time, a bias in modeled irradiance as compared to measurement could result from several reasons, including model bias and biased calibration of the irradiance instrument. Instrument issues might be identified and corrected by deploying redundant sensors. I've seen people address model bias by applying an empirical scalar to the clear sky irradiance. 

Please note that we have a google group pvlib-python for pvlib use questions, and we prefer to keep this forum for issues and discussion of the code itself.

